12. The priest’s god is in the sacred fire,
for ascetics in the heart he lies,
for fools god is within an idol,
and everywhere for the wise.

4. An officer is not greedless;
a puritan does not care for make-up;
a fool cannot speak sweetly,
nor frankly can a trickster.

10
1. Check by looking
while taking each step;
with a cloth filter
when drinking water;
with your books
before you speak;
in the mind reflect
before any action.

3. A beggar is the adversary
of one who is avaricious;
of one who is foolish,
a teacher is the foe;
her husband is the enemy
of a woman adulterous;
and the moon an antagonist
of all who are burglars.

2. An elephant is by a goad controlled;
is that hook as big as the animal?
With a lamp lit, darkness disappears;
is the lamp greater than the dark?
Hills shatter, when struck by lightning;
is that just a flash of light?
In glory does true strength reside;
why believe in just the size?

8. All meals are festive for a priest,
for cows it is fresh grass,
for wives it is a happy husband,
and Krishna’s feet are for me the feast.

10. The hope-fulfilling tree is wood,
the wish-granting gem a stone,
and just a hill is the great Sumeru;
the sun is sharp, the moon decays,
and full of salt is all the ocean;
Kama is a bodiless god, Bali but a demon,
the cow divine is just an animal;
to what can I compare you, Rama?

7. They indeed live, within whom merit
and virtue also are alive;
for one in whom both these are absent,
living is just fruitless.

11. The sandal tree, even cut down,
does not give up its fragrance;
even old, the lordly elephant,
does not its love play abandon;
sugar cane also keeps its sweetness
even when put into a press;
and, though poor, a noble person
does not give up good character.

6. May great wealth not come to me,
from someone else’s deep distress,
from transgression of dharma rules,
or surrender to an enemy.

4. Look for merit, not just beauty,
for character, not family,
for accomplishment, not just learning,
for comfort, not just prosperity.

6. What for a peacock is your love,
for a ruler, any love,
for a courtesan, making love,
or only your love for a beggar?

5. The crow stays not in a lotus pond,
or the swan in waters of a well;
nor in its cave an angry lion;
or lowly folk on seats auspicious;
bad women do not for good men look,
but go out with evil fellows;
how can all these be in places
not by their natures ordained?

11. One who lives on what he earns
by his own work and proper duty;
his home is by the visitors sought;
his passions are under control,
and he always loves his wife—
that best of men attains salvation.
